I mean taking life easy.

Oh, man, that is something.
You don't know what you've missed, for instance, until you find out that you haven't been under that old pine tree.

And all that, you know, I run into people on the street and they'll shake hands with me and pat me on the back and say, Jelly, I listen to every broadcast and you're really the best I ever heard.
Well, I appreciate that to a certain extent.
And of course, it makes you feel pretty good.
But still, you hear that so much, so much, every day, every day.
And then you go on down the street and you run into a fellow and he shakes hands with you, you know, and he says, you know, I've been listening to your programs and I just thought you boys was
Just there having a big time, just carrying on more or less, just a bunch of fun and foolishness.
But he says, you know, you mentioned one day there, you mentioned something about improving pastures.
And he said, you know, I'll be honest with you.
He said, that kind of got me to thinking.
And he said, when I got home, I couldn't, I just kept thinking about it.
I couldn't get it off my mind.
And he said, I decided that you had a good point there.
And he says, you know, Jelly, he was talking to me.
Jelly, that's me.
He says, I've just got to admit that I thought it was a good idea, and I've got an improved pasture.
I fenced up my pasture, and I pulled my cows out of the woods and put them in this pasture.
And he told me, he said, you'd be surprised.
He says, of course, this was several years back, friends.
And he said, you'd be surprised at how much better cattle I'm raising and how much better my timber looks.
He went into details to tell me how the young timber was coming on, the cows and hogs and things like that.

they wasn't there to eat them and they grew up into little little trees and and was just growing along fine didn't any of them get bit down or nipped down he told me he's keeping the fire out of them and that man was just tickled to death and he went on to tell me he said you know and some of my neighbors has kind of noticed my improvements and uh they they've started the same thing and uh it's it's really it's really good this man told me he went on to tell me he says you know
One or two acres of improved pasture will support a cow the year round.
Now, this is his figures along with, well, this is really something.
Now, listen to this.
One or two acres of improved pasture will support a cow year round when it takes 15 or 20 times as many acres of unimproved woods range to provide enough food for one cow.
And then she don't get it the year round.
Ain't that awful?
Think that over.

Friends, when you own your own land, well, you're your own landlord, and you're the master.
You're the boss.
Now, you can do whatever you please on that land.
Just do anything that you want to, as long as you don't affect the other fellow, the other people, or the other people's land.
Now, that's about burning.
When you start to burn, well, you can burn yours off if you want to.
The point I want to get over is this, friends.
The important thing
is that a lot of our biggest and worst woods fires here in the south start with such burning.
Now, it's usually more than one man's land that's hit by such fires as these, and that's the real danger, because more and more folks don't want their land burned off.
You can drive down the road today, and you'll notice on the side of the road, you can see it anywhere, in any section of the country.
Where they've tore down the old house, the unpainted old house, used to sit there.
You can see it in progress.
You can see part of them tore down, partly tore down.
You can see where they're building back a nice, modern, new house there.
Well, friends, if you look right the other side of that house, you'll notice that man has a nice, fenced-up pasture with some good-looking...
cattle are grazing around on it.

I'll guarantee you, you're going down the road a little further, and you'll see that old unpainted house is standing there, and Joe Blow lives in it, and he don't care if that house is good enough for him, and if you'll just notice what few cows he's got, if he's got any, he's out there hustling and scuffling for a living out in them woods, and that's right.
I mean, you already know that.
There's no use of me going into that, but we just got to do more about this burning, and
More and more folks are going in for these improved pastures.
In the hill country, the heavy grazing, burning, that ruins the power of the land to hold the good water that the Lord sends down for us to use.
And we get terrible flash floods in some sections of the country where people do these sort of things.
People suffer pretty bad from some of them, too.
Of course, there's a lot of you out there that already know that.
You might have had it happen to you at one time or other.
And it's happening more and more frequently because these lands have been abused.
And you're just going to have to pitch in there and help us to try to take care of that sort of thing, friends, in our coastal plains country as well as in the hills.
We are gradually coming to see that these improved pastures is the answer to a lot of things.
Now, we can have good cattle, good timber, better kind of living all around.
We just put out a little.
and change some of these old foggy ideas and ways of thinking.
Friends, there's a few that haven't changed their mind yet.
There is a few, I'm sorry to say.
But they're gradually coming on across, and they will.

if you build a good pasture and separate those two.
